#Text=William
#Text=Hunter ( publisher )
#Text=William Hunter ( died August 14 , 1761 ) was a colonial American newspaper publisher , book publisher , and printer for the colony of Virginia .
#Text=Biography
#Text=Hunter was born in Yorktown , Virginia at an unknown date in the early eighteenth century . [ 1 ]
#Text=His parents were William Hunter Sr. ( d. 1742 ) , a merchant of Elizabeth City County , and Mary Ann Hunter ( d. 1743 ) .
#Text=Shortly after the deaths of Hunter 's parents , his sister Elizabeth married John Holt , a merchant , printer , and the mayor of Williamsburg ( 1752 — 1753 ) . [ 2 ]
#Text=Since all of Hunter 's sisters were minor children and had no parents , they moved in with Elizabeth and her new husband at his house . [ 2 ]

#Text=Hunter and his sisters lived in the large house of the " Ravenscroft property " ( two half-acre lots ) owned by Holt from 1745 to 1754 at the corner of Nicholson and Botetourt Streets in Williamsburg .

column1: #Text=Hunter was then the owner of the property after Holt 's death in 1754 , until his death in 1761 . [ 3 ]
#Text=Hunter was a journeyman apprentice under Virginia 's first " public printer " ( " printer to the public " ) William Parks . [ 1 ]
#Text=He was an adult in 1749 and was the foreman of Parks ' print shop . [ 4 ]
#Text=Upon Parks ’ death in 1750 , Hunter took over his position as the official government " public printer " for the colony of Virginia . [ 5 ]
#Text=He was the " public printer " for the House of Burgesses in the colony of Virginia from 1751 to 1761 . [ 1 ] [ 6 ]
#Text=Hunter 's salary was increased from Parks ' last salary of £280 per year to a yearly salary of £300 when he became the official " public printer " for Virginia in 1751 .
#Text=His salary was increased to £350 per year in 1759 . [ 6 ]
#Text=Hunter 's print shop foreman was Joseph Royle . [ 7 ]

#Text=The print shop where Hunter did his daily work for Parks on Duke of Gloucester Street was only about a block away from where he lived at the " Ravenscroft property " at the time he was an apprentice working for Parks . [ 3 ]

column1: #Text=Hunter did the printing of the Virginia Gazette and took over the newspaper upon Parks ' death on April 1 , 1750 . [ 8 ]
#Text=He remained publisher of the Virginia Gazette from January 3 , 1751 until his death in April 1761 . [ 1 ]
#Text=Hunter started his own identity of the Gazette with " no . 1 " in February 1751 . [ 9 ]
#Text=It contained news of the Virginia colony , neighboring colonies , and news from England and parts of Europe .
#Text=Hunter bought out Parks ' print shop in 1753 for £288 for the printing presses and associated equipment . [ 10 ]
#Text=Hunter was a close friend of Benjamin Franklin . [ 1 ]
#Text=In 1753 , he and Franklin were appointed deputy postmaster general as co-directors of the colonies . [ 1 ] [ 11 ]
#Text=Franklin was responsible for the northern areas and Hunter was responsible for areas south of Annapolis , Maryland , a position Hunter held until his death . [ 11 ]

#Text=Hunter 's main work consisted of printing the laws of Virginia , the publication of the Virginia Gazette newspaper , and maintaining a bookstore . [ 1 ]

#Text=In 1754 , Hunter printed George Washington 's first official report , The Journal of Major George Washington : An Account of His First Official Mission , Made as Emissary from the Governor of Virginia to the Commandant of the French Forces on the Ohio , October 1753-January 1754 . [ 12 ] [ 13 ] [ 14 ]
